/jefferson/chronology.html); James G. Swan, Almost Out of the World (Tacoma: Washington State Historical Society, 1971), 9-17; "Decennial Census Counts of Population for Cities and Town," Washington State Office of Financial Management website accessed February 27, 2014 (http://www.ofm.wa.gov/pop/census.asp); "Biographical Note," Guide to the James Gilchrist Swan Papers: 1833-1909, Northwest Digital Archives website accessed February 28, 2014 (http://nwda.orbiscascade.org/ark:/80444/xv77646); Jeff Chew, "Railroads Gone, But Left Mark on Peninsula; Train Lines Often Determined a Town's Status," Peninsula Daily News, February 13, 2011 (www.peninsuladailynews.com); W. H. Ruffner, A Report on Washington Territory (New York: Fleming, Brewster, & Alley, 1889); Meribeth Meixner Reed, "Describing the Life Cycle of U.S. Marine Hospital #17, Port Townsend, Washington, 1855-1933," Military Medicine, April 2005, pp. 259-267; Herbert G. Lull, et al., "A Survey of the Port Townsend Public Schools," Bulletin of the University of Washington, August 1915, available at (http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=pst.000052852275;view=1up;seq=3); "Water Quality -- History," City of Port Townsend website accessed March 2, 2014 (http://cityofpt.us/waterquality.htm); "Washington -- Jefferson County," National Register of Historic Places website accessed March 4, 2014 (http://www.nationalregisterofhistoricplaces.com/wa/Jefferson/state.html); HistoryLink.org Online Encyclopedia of Washington State History, "Victor Smith forcibly moves the U.S. Customs Port of Entry for Washington Territory from Port Townsend to Port Angeles on August 1, 1862" (by Daryl C. McClary), "Port Angeles -- Thumbnail History" (by Kit Oldham), "1870 Census ... " (by John Caldbick), "Alfred A. Plummer and Charles Bachelder settle on the site of future Port Townsend on April 24, 1851" (by Kit Oldham), "The Washington Territorial Legislature incorporates the city of Port Townsend on January 16, 1860" (by Kit Oldham), "Swan, James G. (1818-1900)" (by Kit Oldham), "Triangle of Fire -- The Harbor Defenses of Puget Sound (1897-1953)" (by Daryl C. McClary), "Crown Zellerbach's National Paper Products Mill in Port Townsend starts operation on October 6, 1928" (by Daryl C. McClary), and "Treaty of Point No Point, 1855," www.historylink.org/ (accessed March 3, 2014).


